If you learn to tune it, even can forget about drivers of power keys.

124
00:18:00,950 --> 00:18:02,870
Awesome harmonic isolation.

125
00:18:04,150 --> 00:18:06,730
Works this ferrite.

126
00:18:07,030 --> 00:18:09,750
Tested it above 2 MHz.

127
00:18:10,390 --> 00:18:14,010
Signal from it will show later on oscilloscope.

128
00:18:14,010 --> 00:18:19,850
Well and visible that this part, little terminal block shown here.

129
00:18:20,150 --> 00:18:23,490
This is TC4093 chip.

130
00:18:24,010 --> 00:18:37,390
And want to draw your attention that TC4420 driver has heat sink that I with help of two little wires soldered to board.

131
00:18:38,510 --> 00:18:41,170
Under heat sink we have thermal paste.

132
00:18:41,170 --> 00:18:43,070
What's the purpose?

133
00:18:44,030 --> 00:18:51,410
These drivers aren't developed at all by manufacturer for work in such high frequencies.

134
00:18:51,570 --> 00:19:00,230
And this schematic can be used freely up to 2.5 MHz depending, well maybe even above.

135
00:19:00,670 --> 00:19:02,430
Because transistors allow.

136
00:19:03,130 --> 00:19:06,950
And this chip also allows working at these frequencies.

137
00:19:06,950 --> 00:19:17,350
And driver itself, it starts heating somewhere when frequency approaches range 1.6-1.7 MHz.

138
00:19:18,150 --> 00:19:22,340
Its heating already noticeable, is about 50 degrees.

139
00:19:23,110 --> 00:19:25,330
But still I used heat sink.

140
